Model Card: Adaptive Bayesian Black Box Optimisation (BBO) Strategy

1. Model Overview

Model name
Adaptive Bayesian Black Box Optimisation (BBO)
Type
Sequential Bayesian optimisation framework with adaptive strategy selection.
Version
Capstone implementation – Iterations 0–10
Core components
•	Surrogate models: Gaussian Processes (Matérn, RBF), Random Forests
•	Acquisition functions: Expected Improvement (EI), Upper Confidence Bound (UCB), Thompson Sampling (TS), and mixtures
•	Search regimes: Global BO, local exploitation, Trust Regions, TuRBO variants
This is not a single fixed algorithm, but a structured optimisation approach that adapts its components in response to observed function behaviour.

2. Intended Use
Suitable use cases
•	Optimising unknown, expensive black box functions with limited evaluation budgets.
•	Problems where function structure is unknown a priori and must be inferred from data.
•	Educational or research settings focusing on decision making in Bayesian optimisation, not just final performance.
•	Scenarios requiring transparency and traceability of optimisation decisions.
Uses to avoid
•	Fully automated settings requiring no human interpretation or intervention.
•	Problems with strict real time constraints (high latency per iteration).
•	Situations where strong guarantees of global optimality are required.
•	Benchmarking scenarios that assume a single, static optimisation algorithm.

3. Strategy and Technical Details (Across Ten Rounds)

•	Overall philosophy
The approach follows a three phase logic that emerged empirically rather than being imposed upfront:
1.	Exploration – identify promising regions.
2.	Diagnosis – infer function geometry and failure modes.
3.	Exploitation / validation – refine and confirm the optimal solution.
•	Evolution across rounds
•	Early rounds (Weeks 0–2)
Emphasis on global exploration using GP based BO with EI or UCB.
Goal: detect gradients, multimodality, or potential optima.
•	Middle rounds (Weeks 3–6)
Strategic experimentation with:
o	Alternative surrogates (e.g. Random Forests),
o	Mixed acquisition functions,
o	Trust region constraints.
These rounds revealed model–function mismatches (e.g. GP smoothness vs. irregular functions).
•	Late rounds (Weeks 7–10)
Transition to locally adaptive methods (TuRBO, forced local EI, anisotropic refinement).
At this stage, the objective shifted from “finding something better” to confirming whether improvement was theoretically plausible.
Across functions, stagnation was interpreted as evidence, not failure, when supported by repeated local confirmation.


4. Performance Summary

Evaluation scope
The approach was applied across eight distinct black box functions with varying dimensionality and landscape structure.

Metrics used
•	Best observed objective value (best y).
•	Improvement over time (convergence curves).
•	Stability of the optimum across iterations.
•	Qualitative diagnostics (e.g. input–output scatter plots, trust region behaviour).

Summary of results
•	Early convergence on unimodal or boundary optimum functions.
•	Late improvements only when changing the search regime, not just parameters.
•	Clear empirical evidence that one optimisation strategy does not fit all functions.
•	In several cases, the best result was achieved early and subsequently validated rather than surpassed, consistent with the true function geometry.
Performance was therefore evaluated not only on absolute optima, but on appropriateness of decisions relative to the function behaviour.

5. Assumptions and Limitations

Key assumptions
•	Observed samples are representative enough to infer global function structure.
•	Repeated local confirmation implies absence of superior distant optima.
•	Bayesian surrogates provide meaningful uncertainty estimates under limited data.

Limitations and failure modes
•	Strong dependence on early signals: misleading early observations can bias later focus.
•	Reduced global coverage once local exploitation is prioritised.
•	Not robust to highly deceptive functions with multiple rare, isolated optima.
•	Requires human judgement to interpret diagnostics and adjust strategy.
The approach trades theoretical completeness for empirical efficiency and interpretability.

6. Ethical Considerations and Transparency
Transparency and reproducibility
•	All optimisation decisions are explicitly documented (model choice, AF, radius changes).
•	The reasoning behind strategy changes is traceable to observed data patterns.
•	This transparency enables: 
o	Reproducibility by other researchers,
o	Post hoc auditing of optimisation decisions,
o	Responsible adaptation to real world problems.
Real world adaptation In applied settings, such transparency reduces the risk of:
•	Over trusting automated optimisation outputs,
•	Misinterpreting stagnation as failure,
•	Deploying optimisation strategies beyond their valid regime.

Reflection on Model Card Adequacy
This model card deliberately balances detail and abstraction:
•	It avoids listing every parameter value (which is documented elsewhere),
•	It focuses on decision logic, assumptions, and empirical behaviour.
Adding substantially more detail (e.g. week by week hyperparameters) would reduce clarity rather than increase usefulness, obscuring the core contribution:
a defensible, evidence driven optimisation process rather than a single algorithmic recipe.

